article.description:
Shannon Johnson's hot shooting made Dee
Brown's WNBA coaching debut a success.
article.headline: Ex-NBA star Brown wins coaching debut
article.linkText: Hot-shot Johnson makes Brown a winner in Miracle coaching debut
article.story:
ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) -- Shannon Johnson's hot shooting made Dee Brown's WNBA coaching debut a success. Johnson scored 17 of her 22 points in the opening 10 minutes as the Orlando Miracle beat the Detroit Shock 80-66 Thursday night. "The first win is nice, just to get it over with. Better sooner than later,'' said Brown, a 12-year NBA veteran who took the Miracle job in April. "It's great fun to coach. I want to compete and give our team a chance to win.'' Brown replaced Carolyn Peck, who had a record of 44-52 in three seasons with Orlando before taking the coaching job at the University of Florida. Johnson couldn't miss early, hitting four of her first six shots from the field and eight of nine from the foul line. After her 3-pointer with 10:22 remaining in the first half put the Miracle ahead 25-18, she had more than doubled the scoring output of her teammates, 17-8. "We have confidence in Dee,'' said Johnson, who also had five assists. "He knows what it's like to be out there. He doesn't seem nervous at all. He's a winner.'' Nykesha Sales also had 22 points for the Miracle, who posted their first victory in four season-opening games. "We wanted to win this for Dee, although he said he isn't worried about what people think of him,'' said Sales, who was 10-for-11 from the foul line. Rookie Swin Cash had 16 points to lead Detroit in its season-opener, while Wendy Palmer had 15 and Deanna Nolan 13. The Shock committed 26 turnovers, 16 in the first half. "I thought we ran our offense well once we got past the pressure,'' Detroit coach Greg Williams said. "I was really surprised we were only down 42-48 after the first half, because it seemed like every possession we were just glad to get it over halfcourt.'' Orlando took control of the game midway through the second half. Holding Detroit without a field goal for a 5:28 span, the Miracle scored nine straight points to take a 65-55 lead with 6:46 remaining.

Game notes
Orlando guard Adrienne Johnson scored eight points in her return from a year of injury rehabilitation. Johnson ruptured her right Achilles' tendon in training camp last season. ... The attendance of 13,111 was the second-largest in Miracle history. ... NBA players Chucky Atkins of the Detroit Pistons and Chris Gatling of the Miami Heat were in the crowd. ... Detroit's record in season-opening games fell to 1-4.
